<section id="the-treatment-problem" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Pharmacological Mismatch</h2>
  <p>IBS affects between 10 and 15 percent of the global population, a figure that has remained stubbornly consistent across epidemiological surveys for two decades. Stress-related onset accounts for a substantial proportion of those cases. Fewer than 30 percent of patients achieve what clinicians classify as adequate symptom control with current standard-of-care treatments. That is not a rounding error. That is a systematic failure rate that the field has largely absorbed as an unfortunate feature of a complex disorder rather than evidence that the treatment model is structurally wrong.</p>
  <p>The dominant pharmacological approach to stress-related GI disorders — SSRIs, SNRIs, tricyclic antidepressants at low doses, general anxiolytics — operates primarily on the HPA axis and central serotonin systems. The logic is coherent as far as it goes: if stress is the upstream driver, modulate the stress response. The problem, which the 2026 pathway-specificity finding makes explicit, is that these interventions are aimed at the trunk of the tree, before it branches. For patients whose symptoms are driven by the visceral pain sensitization pathway — the mast cell and peripheral serotonin route — central serotonin modulation is at least in the right general neighborhood, even if the targeting is imprecise. For patients whose symptoms are driven by the motility pathway — the vagal tone and enteric neuron density route — an SSRI is pharmacologically addressing a different problem in a different location. The drug is not wrong in principle. It is wrong for that patient's specific mechanism.</p>
  <p>This is not a subtle distinction. It is the difference between treating hypertension with a beta-blocker in a patient whose hypertension is driven by renal artery stenosis. The drug class is cardiovascular. The target is wrong.</p>

